03943nam a22005535i 9780674972469DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172016mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749724697 a10.4159/97806749724692doi  a(DE-B1597)479772  a(OCoLC)984656832  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aK260 7aLAW0520002bisacsh04a340/.1152231 aFriedman, Lawrence M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aImpact :bHow Law Affects Behavior /cLawrence M. Friedman. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2017] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Very Short Prologue -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Getting Out the Message -- t3. An Anatomy of Compliance -- t4. A Typology of Responses -- t5. Rewards and Punishments: The Punishment Side -- t6. Rewards and Punishments: Incentives and the Civil Side -- t7. The Pressure of Peers -- t8. The Inner Voice -- t9. Factors in Harmony; Factors in Battle -- t10. A Concluding Word -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLaws and regulations are ubiquitous, touching on many aspects of individual and corporate behavior. But under what conditions are laws and rules actually effective? A huge amount of recent work in political science, sociology, economics, criminology, law, and psychology, among other disciplines, deals with this question. But these fields rarely inform one another, leaving the state of research disjointed and disorganized. Lawrence M. Friedman finds order in this cacophony. Impact gathers recent findings into one overarching analysis and lays the groundwork for a cohesive body of work in what Friedman labels “impact studies.” The first important factor that has a bearing on impact is communication. A rule or law has no effect if it never reaches its intended audience. The public’s fund of legal knowledge, the clarity of the law, and the presence of information brokers all influence the flow of information from lawmakers to citizens. After a law is communicated, subjects sometimes comply, sometimes resist, and sometimes adjust or evade. Three clusters of motives help shape which reaction will prevail: first, rewards and punishments; second, peer group influences; and third, issues of conscience, legitimacy, and morality. When all of these factors move in the same direction, law can have a powerful impact; when they conflict, the outcome is sometimes unpredictable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCompliance. 0aEffectiveness and validity of law. 0aLawxPsychological aspects. 0aLawxSocial aspects. 0aObedience (Law). 0aSociological jurisprudence. 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311063858540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067497246940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674972469423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674972469.jpg  a978-3-11-063858-5  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles